If this land is bad, I don’t want to be good. 

These are my top 10 favorite memories from our fall break trip in the Black Hills, South Dakota. 

📸1, 4 & 9: The wildlife – mountain goats in Custer State Park (can you spot them?), bison in Wind Caves, and Bighorn Sheep in Badlands National Park

📸2 & 3: Finishing my #52hikechallenge on the coolest hike in Badlands National Park. 

📸5: The scenic drives through narrow tunnels. The roads here are just more fun. 

📸6: Getting to experience iconic tourist attractions, like Mount Rushmore, without any crowds! If you’re up for a short hike, you can have the views to yourself – especially in the fall. Not to mention, those fall colors.

📸7 & 📹8: Chasing waterfalls and living in the moment with my kids– jumping through a freezing cold waterfall after my son making me laugh with one liners like “watch the pro” and you’ve got to make an entrance.” 

📸10: Watching (and hearing) my daughter zoom by at full speed on the mountain coaster at Rush Mountain Adventure Park,  yelling “eat my dust!” 

Which picture/video is your fave? 

#hifromSD #forever605 #blackhills #badlands #greatfacesgreatplaces #southdakota

Rumor has it that if you hike a mile or more in a national park, you will leave about 90% of the visitors behind. This was certainly true with our experience at this national monument.

📌SAVE this post for the best views of Mount Rushmore, trail details, and how to avoid crowds. 

The best views (in my opinion) of Mount Rushmore are not from the Avenue of Flags, but instead are on the Presidential Loop Hiking Trail. Here are the details:

🥾1 mile loop*
⛰️You can make this shorter or longer depending on the route. It can be an out and back, lollipop loop or full loop. I recommend a loop– starting from the Avenue of the Flags hiking clockwise on the Presidential Trail and then up the Nature Trail after the Borglum View Terrace. 
♿The out and back route is an accessible option without stairs
💪If you want more of a challenge (and more stairs) take the loop counter clockwise.
🚽Restrooms along the Avenue of Flags and at the Borglum View Terrace 
🐾Dogs are not allowed on this trail
💰Cost for parking is $10 but there is no charge to enter the monument
🍦Be sure to treat yourself to ice cream (Thomas Jefferson’s recipe!) after your hike at Carver’s Cafe!
📍Ancestral lands of the Lakota People
🌎Please remember to Leave No Trace, be respectful of the land and the other visitors, stay on trail, take only pictures, and leave what you find. 

In addition to hiking further out than the typical viewpoints at popular places, some other ways to avoid crowds are:
–Go early or late in the day. This trail would be beautiful at sunrise (the monument opens at 5:00 a.m.) with the lighting on the rock. The shadows of the sun are not as ideal for sunset. 
–Consider visiting during the off season. We visited over fall break in mid-October and we felt like we had this beautiful area all to ourselves. With 2.5 million people visiting Mount Rushmore each year, it is worth it to avoid the summer crowds and get a more peaceful experience. This peaceful feeling was true throughout our entire visit to the Black Hills this time of year!

#hifromSD #forever605 #greatfacesgreatplaces #mountrushmore #hike49 #52hikechallenge

– Family dinner time: complete with highs and lows and buffaloes. This is especially special now that my mom recently moved to Colorado and gets to join us.

I’ll be relying on those Safeway® Ready Meals, easy recipe suggestions, and even the Order Ahead option for Thanksgiving for my family dinner contribution and I don’t feel the least bit guilty about it!

I’m in denial that it’s mid-November, so I’m just going to live vicariously through these summer photos instead of accepting the reality.

Plus, I’ve got some ground to cover in documenting my 2023 hikes and the end of 2023 is knocking at the door. In early July we hiked to Middle Blue Lakes and camped for a couple of nights. The first day was a big day (2300 ft gain), so the next day we did a short little hike to Upper Blue Lakes – #hike34 of my #52hikechallenge. 

These lakes in the Mount Sneffels Wilderness are gorgeous from every angle, but are most special from above. There was too much snow to climb higher, so we have some unfinished business as I would love to get to the top of Blue Lakes Pass (or better yet Sneffels) one day!

‼️So let’s talk about the changes for “one day” because there will be some big ones coming if you want to access this trail….

Due to the increase in visitors to this area (one study counted 509 visitors just in ONE DAY in July last year!), improper waste disposal, illegal campfires, and the negative impacts of natural habitats, the USFS announced last month that there will be a new permit system in the future. What they are currently proposing is (starting May 1, 2025), they will allow 40 day use permits and 24 overnight permits per day. They will also no longer allow camping above treeline (makes sense although it was soooo beautiful), camping outside of 4 designated sites near Lower Blue Lakes. And you will be required to pack out your 💩 (which is already recommended using wagbags).

Is this hike on your Colorado bucket list? What do you think of the proposed reservation system? 

My personal opinion is that the reservation system and the new rules in place are necessary…BUT…I am shocked at how few permits they are proposing for both day and overnight hikers. I’d love to hear your thoughts!

If you are lucky to visit this special place next summer, please be sure to Leave No Trace, pack out ALL of your waste including 💩, stay on the main trail and avoid social trails, have a plan B if the parking lot is full, and camp in designated sites.

#hike34of52 #52hikechallenge2023 #upperbluelake #coloradophotography

I’m not going to lie….I don’t do so well with the “it’s about the journey, not the destination” mentality when it comes to hiking. I can get there with some hikes, but when it’s one I have had on my bucket list for years, it hurts to have to turn around. 

On #hike35 this year, we attempted Columbine Lake on 4th of July (hence the F-16s flying BELOW us…it was rad). 

We took an alternate route via Bullion King Lake (as opposed to Ophir) due to snowy conditions. But even still, the snow + ice + vertical slope was not possible this early in the year. We stopped for lunch and could see Columbine in the distance. I was sad. But…to make the most of it, we climbed up an unnamed 13er to feel a sense of accomplishment. It was a damn good consolation for not getting to our destination. 

Below are our stats for this random beautiful hike without a name. Let’s call it…
 
✨BULLION KING LAKE + UNNAMED 13ER✨

🥾6.2 miles out and back 

⛰️1700 feet elevation gain

🐾Dogs are allowed on the trail, so please be sure to pick up their 💩. 

🚽None, so plan accordingly

💰Free

📍Ancestral lands of the Diné Bikéyah, Pueblos and Núu-agha-tʉvʉ-pʉ̱ (Ute) People

🌎The San Juan Mountains are some of the most beautiful in all of Colorado. Please help keep them that way by practicing Leave No Trace. Pack out what you brought in, take only pictures, be prepared for wintery conditions even in the summer, and have a plan B!

👉Follow our #52hikechallenge2023 journey in my guides and story highlight! Let’s see how close I can get to documenting them all by the end of the year!

Despite the beauty that we did see,, this hike remains in the “unfinished business” category. Do you have an unfinished business list?

One of my favorite holiday traditions is cutting down our Christmas tree. With a few years under our belt, I feel like we have got this down so we are sharing some tips for a successful tree cutting experience! #AD

🎄5 Tips for a Successful Tree Cutting Experience🎄

1️⃣ Pack yummy snacks – I used the Safeway App® and the FreshPass® to deliver snacks and food right to our door. We packed food for the day, as well as yummy treats for the drive to the mountains. 

2️⃣ Let the kids help – You have to lower your expectations for the “perfect tree,” but searching for it is fun. The kids love to be involved in picking their favorite tree and even in chopping it down (with supervision). 

3️⃣ Have a tailgate with friends – After we found our tree, we hung out, grilled burgers, and ate freshly baked Safeway chips and 7 layer dip. The kids also had fun sledding and playing in the snow.

4️⃣ Bring festive treats – You can use the Safeway App® to easily browse holiday inspired food. We warmed up hot cocoa and added holiday flare with candy canes and peppermint whipped cream. We also ordered Safeway Signature SELECT Mistletoe Crunch, which was a big hit. 

5️⃣ Get a permit in advance – Check your local forest service for tree cutting permits and local rules so you know where you can go and what you can cut. 

And of course…have fun! While you may not find the picture perfect tree, you’ll have a story to tell and will make some holiday memories. 

Have you ever cut down your own Christmas tree?

Con·fi·dence: 

a feeling of self-assurance arising from one’s appreciation of one’s own abilities or qualities: “she’s brimming with confidence.”

Nope. That’s not me. Yes, I am a confident person in some regards. But I can also be very nervous when it comes to outdoor adventures, especially when I am alone with my kids. Those “what ifs” start creeping in. And the truth is that a lot of those “what ifs” are real possibilities because there can be a lot of risk involved in hiking. 

But I do connect with the alternate definition of confidence (the feeling or belief that one can rely on someone or something). Because I have confidence in my kids and my parenting on the trail. I am confident that they will tell me if they are scared. I am confident that they will listen to me if I tell them something is too dangerous. I am confident that I will make the safe call to turn around if something feels too sketchy. 

This confidence has come from time & training in the outdoors. Hiking is fun, but there are a lot of teachable moments on the trail about risks and safety. I try to weave these lessons into our hikes so that 1) they will make safe decisions and 2) I can trust them – which leads to me being a more confident adventurer with them. 

Cue our #hike36. Dogs are not allowed so Bryce stayed back and I took them on my own. This was one where I really needed another adult. Both kids needed assistance at times, there were some sketchy parts, and I was having anxious moments while trying to appear “confident” for my kids. In the end, we turned back just shy of the top and I feel 100% confident in that decision. We still got to dance under the falls and they had a great story to tell Daddy. 

✨EAST VAIL FALLS✨

🥾A *hard* 1 mile up & down 

⛰️325 ft gain

🐾Dogs are NOT allowed on this trail

🚽None

💰Free

📍Ancestral lands of theNúu-agha-tʉvʉ-pʉ̱ (Ute) People

🌎Please practice leave no trace by staying on trail. It is tempting to go off trail as a “safer” option, but that is your signal to turn around. 

👉Follow our #52hikechallenge2023 journey in my guides & story highlight! 

#hike36of52 #vail #eastvailfalls #hikingwithkids #raisinghikers

One thing that I love as much as hiking is live music. 

This year I went to 9 concerts. This included my kids first ever big concert and the BIGGEST concert of the year with just my daughter. While the memories were amazing, the experience in getting my hands on tickets was not.

From long wait times to instantly sold out tickets, it was never a fun time. I missed out on concerts that I would have loved to go to and it’s all thanks to.... #TheMonopoly. 

So join me in standing up for #FairTicketing. Find out how to #BreakThemUp by joining the movement of the @fanfairnesscoalition. The parody band “The Monopoly” made me laugh and cry all at the same time.

Story time…

We first attempted this summit summer of 2021. We were at the trailhead at sunrise, the conditions were perfect, BUT it wasn’t our day. Just shy of the summit in a quick fluke accident, Walker hit the back of his head on a rock and had some significant bleeding. With the help of a trail angel who used to be an EMT, we busted out our first aid kit and acted quickly to get the bleeding to stop. Sidenote, I FULLY believe in trail angels since later the same summer when Walker knocked his front teeth out on a hike (it was a year!), a dentist happened to be hiking past us. What are the chances? Anyway, head injuries are not something to downplay, so we turned around and carried Walker down in the @trail.magik and got him checked out at the hospital. 

After this incident, we always have our @trail.magik and a first aid kit with us. Even though my kids are now too big to be carried (so bittersweet!), it gives me peace of mind to know that I have a way to safely carry them out in case of an emergency. And If you haven’t already heard, @trail.magik is having their biggest sale of the year for another week. All of their carriers are up to 15% off and you can stack my 10% discount code (RAISINGHIKERS10) for up to 25% total! 

Fast forward 3 summers later, we got the chance to attempt this peak again. The feeling of accomplishment in getting to the top was one that I don’t take for granted. ❤️❤️❤️

Here are the deets. As with all 14ers, please know your and your kids’ abilities, pay attention to the signs of altitude sickness, summit early to avoid thunderstorms, and be prepared. 

✨QUANDARY PEAK✨

🥾6.5 miles out & back
⛰️3,500 ft elevation gain – topping out at 14,271 ft
🐾Dogs are allowed, but please know your dog’s abilities and pick up and pack out their 💩
🚽Portapotties at trailhead
💰Parking reservations or shuttle are needed from June-September
📍Ancestral lands of theNúu-agha-tʉvʉ-pʉ̱ (Ute) People
🌎Please practice leave no trace - leave the trail better than you found it and respect wildlife. 

👉Follow our #52hikechallenge2023 journey in my guides & story highlight!

We sat around the Christmas dinner table and answered the question, “what was your favorite memory this year?” Everyone got two because picking one favorite is just too hard. Here were our families’ answers…

Walker: Summiting Sunshine and Red Cloud with Daddy & sunset at White Sands National Park (and also he answered his math tests this year, but that didn’t make the video!) 

Emerson: Seeing Taylor Swift with Mommy & bike riding in Yosemite Valley

Daddy: Backpacking Blue Lakes as a family & Climbing Mount Whitney solo

Me: Sunrise in Bryce Canyon & summiting Pikes Peak with one of my chosen sisters

Even though we did so much this year, 2023 was a year of settling down. It was “slower” than our usual years.  I went back to work, we didn’t do any international travel, and stayed “closer to home.” 

Like most years we experienced both loss and light. We lost family members, but we gained my mom as a neighbor. We almost lost Jasper, and we gained 2 new pets just this week – Mr.Squeaks and Kevin. I’ve dealt with some health (pain) issues, but we are overall healthy. I made new friends, spent time with old friends, saw lots of concerts & musicals, and hiked over 60 hikes. My Southwest buddy pass was wasted since we barely flew this year (if only I had it again next year!!). But this year reminded me how lucky we are to live in Colorado and have so many fun destinations just a road trip away. 

Some runner up that didn’t make the list but were so special were: yurt trip with IG friends in ID, spring break in Arches with our neighbors/friends, Telluride camping in the summer with friends, Maroon Bells in the fall colors, spending time with my BFF in Arizona and riding a horse for the first time, family time in South Dakota, seeing the beautiful blue color of Lake Haiyaha, and our first family 14er all together.

Manatees, also known as sea cows, are migratory creatures who are concentrated in Florida in the winter. Like us, they are seeking warmth in the winter months. 

If you want to swim or snorkel with manatees, the only place that is legal is the Crystal River. This is definitely the “go to spot,” but since my kids were a little apprehensive to swim with these big beauties, we went with a lesser known spot — Weeki Wachee Springs. You may have heard of this spot from the entertaining docuseries, MerPeople. Highly recommend.

Weeki Wachee Springs State Park is perfect for kayaking with kids because you put the kayak in upstream and can essentially float down without much effort. It’s a 3 mile stretch that takes 2 hours with zero paddling, or less if you paddle. Then you take a quick shuttle back. It’s the right amount of time for kids and enough time to increase your chances of seeing manatees. We saw about 8 in our adventure.

Wherever you decide to see manatees, don’t sleep on this unique experience on your Florida vacation!

#manatees #kayaking #paddlelife #weekiwachee #weekiwacheesprings #floridalife

[SAVE] this post for our TOP 5 activities from our South Florida winter vacation to add to your itinerary!

Our winter looked a little different this year as we traded snow for sand. Our winter break falls later than usual–getting out right before Christmas and we don’t go back until Tuesday. Initially I didn’t like this new schedule but now that I work for the school district, I am a fan of more time AFTER the holiday. It’s so nice to have all of the “stress” of Christmas behind us and just time to hang as a family. 

The downside is that Bryce has to go back to work so I needed to find a vacation that I could manage the kids easily during the day while he worked. Beach was the most relaxing choice and Florida the most cost effective option. I didn’t have much planned before we went (besides hanging at the beach and Harry Potter), but we ended up filling our days with lots of fun and some day trips.

Here were our top ✋favorite activities during the week (in no particular order as each of the family had a different favorite):

🐊Spotting alligators (and trying to find crocodiles) at @evergladesnps — We went to Shark Valley Visitor Center and actually ended up seeing the most alligators right outside of the park at Big Cypress National Preserve.

🛶Kayaking with manatees at @weekiwacheesprings – scroll back to  the previous post for more info out this MUST DO experience!

🪄Spending the day at @universalorlando – more to come on how to do this in a day and particularly how to make the most of your time at the Wizarding World of Harry Potter! 

🛥️Sunset boat cruise to search for dolphins in the bay – we didn’t have luck with dolphins that day, but it was still a beautiful ride. 

🌊Swimming at the beach in St. Pete– while it was a little colder than usual during this time in South Florida, it was significantly warmer than Denver, so we made the most of it and got in the water every day.This is what we came for after all! The Gulf of Mexico was so nice for kids because of the minimal waves. 

Which of these Florida activities are you adding to your list?

How to do the Wizarding World of Harry Potter in a day – 🪄SAVE this post!

When planning this trip, this was the post I was hoping to find! With HP World spread across 2 parks in Orlando (Islands of Adventure & Universal Studios), I wasn’t sure if it was possible to see both parks in a day. The answer is…IT IS!! And, if you follow these tips, you will even have time to see the other parts of both parks.

Stay on-site (the 3 are Royal Pacific Resort, Hard Rock Hotel, and Portofino Bay Hotel) the night before. We used Citi Travel Card points + $100 travel voucher we get each year to stay for free for 1 night. With 1 night hotel, you get  early entrance to the park and the EXPRESS PASS free! I was shocked at how expensive the Express Pass was to add to our park tickets. It nearly doubled the cost of our park tickets – which were not cheap. The Express Pass is a gamechanger (and I would probably say a MUST if you want to do anything outside of Harry Potter World). It cut the time in lines by more than half on most rides.

But, Hagrid’s Motor Bike Ride doesn’t have an Express Pass line, which is why I recommend getting to the park early and racing to that ride first. We were on the 1st ferry at 7:00a and in line at the gates at 7:15a. The park opens for early access at 8am and the lines were LONG. However, we ran to the ride and got on in less than 30 min. I kept checking the wait times on the app all day to see if we could ride it for a 2nd time and the wait never dipped below 135 minutes. Just crazy!

After Hagrid’s, get in line for the wand experience at Ollivander’s because that one also gets long and you will want to have your wand for the whole day. Then ride Flight of the Hippogriff and HP & the Forbidden Journey. Take a break, walk the shops, and have butterbeer at Hog’s Head. Then ride the Hogwart’s Express to the Universal side to explore Diagon Alley. 

With this plan you will have plenty of extra time to ride other rides outside of HP.

Is Harry Potter World on your list?

#harrypotter #wizardingworldofharrypotter #harrypotterworld #potterheads #universalorlando

The 1st free entrance day for the National Park System is coming up this Monday (full list in my comments). 

We were lucky to visit 12 National parks this year (7 of them were new to at least one of us in the family) and even visited some on free days! There is no doubt about it…free days are busy. Because they are free. But they also make the parks more accessible, which is awesome. Here are some things to consider when trip planning:

Is this the only time you can visit? Then GO! Don’t miss visiting a park because it’s on a free day. We had a 4 day weekend last April that landed on a free day. At first, I pouted because I knew the crowds would be bigger than usual. And then I checked myself and was grateful that we could do this trip at all. It was epic and the crowds did not impact our trip. 

How many times do you plan on visiting national parks this year? If not many, it may not be worth buying the $80 America the Beautiful Pass. In that case, Go on a free day to avoid the day pass cost.

Are you only visiting for a day or are you planning on a multi-day trip to the park? If it’s a multi-day trip, then I’d plan it on another weekend because the cost savings isn’t going to make a difference if you have to pay for the other days anyway. 

What time of year are you visiting and where? The January date in Colorado, where it’s snowy, isn’t going to make as big of an impact on crowds as the date in August, for example. 

How far are you adventuring into the park? The further you go into the park–even just beyond a mile on trails, the crowds reduce significantly. 

If you go, be patient with entry lines and rangers, be respectful and welcoming to all who are there! Check your privilege when complaining about crowds.  You are not entitled to any type of experience in the park just because you have an annual pass, are a local, or recreate in the outdoors often, or any other reason. The outdoors are for EVERYONE. And as always practice leave no trace and leave these parks better than you found them!

Will you be visiting a national park on this 3 day weekend? 

#nationalparklover #outdoorsisforeveryone #accessibleoutdoors #raisinghikers
